  "number": "2.2",
  "title": "Regression",
  "body": " Regression  This section is coordinated with Freedman, Statistics  , Chapters 8 12.   RMS Error of Fit  Given two lists of numbers with the same number of entries, and given a linear function ( and are constants), the rms error for the line rms error for a line is the rms of the list . (For example, if is an entry in the list and is the corresponding entry in the list , then the corresponding entry in the list is .) We interpret the rms error for a line as a measure of how well performs as a tool for predicting the value that corresponds to a given value. Given an value , the value has a \"prediction error\" equal to . The line is a good prediction tool if the rms error for is low, and the line is a bad prediction tool if the rms error for is high. We interpret the rms error for a line as the size of the typical error that we would observe if we used to predict an unknown value for a given value.   The Regression Line  Among all possible lines, there is one single line with the least possible rms error, called the regression line for on  the regression line . This means that the regression line is the best possible line to use as a prediction tool to guess an unknown corresponding value for a given value. The regression line passes through the point , called the point of averages point of averages  for the lists , and has slope equal to , where is the number called the correlation coefficient correlation coefficient  for the pair of lists . The rms error for the regression line is     The Scatter Diagram  The list of pairs of points from the lists is called the scatter diagram scatter diagram  of the lists . The scatter diagram is said to show linear association linear association  if the points are scattered roughly symmetrically about a linear axis. The size of the correlation coefficient determines the tightness or looseness of scattering of points about the regression line. For near 1, points in the scatter diagram are tightly clustered about the regression line. As approaches 0, the scatter diagram is more and more loosely clustered about the regression line.   A thin vertical strip thin vertical strip  in the scatter diagram is a set of points whose -coordinate lies in a range from , where is a number within the range of entries of the list and is a small increment. If the various sets of values in thin vertical strips (for various values of ) has a similar SD as varies, the scatter diagram is said to be homoscedastic homoscedastic . Otherwise, the scatter diagram is said to be heteroscedastic heteroscedastic .     More on Prediction and Error  Let's write for the -coordinate of a point on the regression line for the -value . Here's a formula The notation is not a standard notation. We use it here merely for convenience. . A residual residual is another name for a vertical error for a data point . The graph of residuals is the set of points . You can see linear association and homoscedasticity (or the lack of either one) very plainly in the graph of residuals: data lists have a linear association if the graph of residuals is roughly symmetric across the -axis; and the data are homoscedastic if the graph of residuals has fairly even densities and vertical ranges in thin vertical strips across the horizontal range of .   shows a comparison of three lines and their rms errors. All three lines pass through the point of averages. The SD line is defined to have positive slope if and negative slope if .  Comparison of Lines and Prediction Errors    line  slope  rms error   regression line       SD line see p.147        average line            Facts about the correlation coefficient   The value of is in the range to . The value of is 1 precisely when all the points on the scatter diagram lie on a straight line.  The correlation coefficient is unitless. The value of does not change if you rescale or .  It is tempting to summarize data using averages, but this has a misleading effect on correlation. Suppose that the points in a scatter diagram are subdivided into subsets, and that each subset is replaced by a single point The correlation for this smaller data set of average points is usually higher (in absolute value) than the correlation for the original scatter diagram. This phenomenon is called ecological correlation ecological correlation .  A strong correlation provides no evidence of a causal link between the variables and .      The Regression Effect and the Regression Fallacy  Start with an -value , somewhere above or below the value . Use the regression line for on to predict the average value for data points whose value is near . Call this prediction . Now use the regression line for on to predict the average value for data points whose value is near . Call this prediction . It will always turn out that is between and . This is due simply to the fact that, for real data, the value of is less than 1. This is called the regression effect regression effect . Any attempt to explain why is between and by any other reason than simply the fact that is called a regression fallacy regression fallacy .    "
