  "title": "Activity on Medical Testing",
  "body": " Activity on Medical Testing  A naturally occuring random genetic mutation called M is found at a rate of in people. A test called T detects mutation M with accuracy. This means that of people with mutation M will test negative, and of people who do not have mutation M will test positive. As part of a medical study with randomly selected participants, Skylar takes test T and the result is positive (that is, the test indicates that Skylar has mutation M). Before getting the positive test result, the best estimate of the chance that Skylar has mutation M is in , which is . How does the positive test result change this estimate?  Problem : Estimate the chance that Skylar has mutation M, knowing that Skylar tested positive for mutation M.  To solve the problem, consider what would happen if everyone in a population of million people got the test for mutation M? Lets name these subgroups of the population.  : people who have mutation M  : people who do not have mutation M  : people whose test result is positive   : people whose test result is negative  It will be helpful to consider further subdivisions of these groups of people.   : people in group A who test positive   : people in group A who test negative   : people in group B who test positive   : people in group B who test negative    Solve the problem.   Estimate how many people are in each group. Hint: start with groups and , then do , , , , then do and last.  Now solve the Problem using the numbers from part 1. Give your solution as a percent, and write a sentence or two to express your reasoning.  Would your answer change if you thought about a population of million instead of million?  Would your answer change if mutation M occurs in of the population, instead of in ?    "
